land to island and the species change. Travel along any gradient—up a mountain, from forest into desert, from low tide to high tide on a shoreline —and again the species change, sometimes abruptly. What explains the patterns of these distributions? Some patterns might be as random as a coin toss. But as with a coin toss, can ecologists differentiate associations caused by a multiplicity of complex, idiosyncratic factors from those structured by some unidentified but simple mechanisms? Can simple mechanisms that structure communities be inferred from observations of which species associations naturally occur? For decades, community ecologists have debated about whether the patterns are random or show the geographically pervasive effect of competition between species. Bringing this vigorous debate up to date, this book undertakes the identification and interpretation of nature’s large-scale patterns of species co-occurrence to offer insight into how nature truly works. Patterns in Nature explains the computing and conceptual advances that allow us to explore these issues. It forces us to reexamine assumptions about species distribution patterns and will be of vital importance to ecologists and conservationists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiogeography. 0aBiotic communities. 0aNull models (Ecology) 0aNull models (Ecology). 0aPattern formation (Biology) 0aPattern formation (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aspecies, nature, natural, ecology, ecologists, adaptation, change, distributions, multiplicity, mechanisms, geography, conservation, conservationists, formation, biogeography, co-occurrences, robert macarthur, birds, islands, environment, cuckoo, bats, representative, the galapagos, vanuatu, characteristics, reciprocal specialization, nestedness, solomon, science, scientific, mount kupe ca